<H3> <TI>   Further Reports on U.S.-Japan Economic, Trade Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reports on U.S.-Japan Economic, Trade Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kakizawa, Other Ministers May Visit U.S. </H4>

<F P=102> OW0906140994 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 9 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 9 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0906140994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 8 June, a top official of the Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry [MITI] explained a view that in 
an attempt to end negotiations in priority areas prior to the 
Japan-U.S. comprehensive economic talks, it is likely that 
ministers, including Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa and MITI 
Minister Eijiro Hata, will visit the United States and hold 
ministerial meetings with U.S. Trade Representative Mickey 
Kantor and other secretaries. 
  Regarding goals of the negotiations, the same senior 
official 
said that "details of a report, which will be submitted to the 
Hata-Clinton talks, will be worked out in deputy ministerial 
talks before the [Naples] summit." In this way, he explained 
the idea of producing some results before the summit in the four 
priority areas -- government procurement, auto and auto parts, 
insurance, and export promotion and competitive power. 

</TEXT>

