<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Panel To Review Security Arrangements With U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Panel To Review Security Arrangements With U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0906120494 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 9 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 7 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0906120494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At the 13th meeting at the prime minister's 
official residence on 8 June, members of the "Defense Policy 
Council," an advisory panel to the prime minister, agreed to 
"review the significance" of the Japan-U.S. security pact. The 
security agreement was the main pillar of Japan's security 
policy in the Cold War era. However, considering changes 
following the end of the Cold War era, the panel has decided to 
review the significance of the security pact. 
  The panel plans to discuss specifics at future meetings. At 
present, there is a strong opinion within the panel that "the 
pact should not be defined as mere the framework of Japan-U.S. 
security arrangements, but it should be characterized as a 
nucleus of a security system in the Asia-Pacific region." 
  Besides conventional cooperation such as assuming burdens 
for 
maintaining the U.S. forces in Japan, the panel is expected to 
discuss giving more support to the U.S. forces stationed in the 
region. Concluding an acquisition and cross-servicing agreement 
(ACSA), which allows Japan and the U.S. forces to mutually 
provide goods such as fuel, is also a topic to be discussed by 
the panel. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-28478 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas112__a94013" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-112-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kakizawa Comments on Enactment of Emergency Laws </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kakizawa Comments on Enactment of Emergency Laws </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0906134994 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 9 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0906134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At the House of Representatives' Budget Committee 
meeting in the morning of 8 June, Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa 
touched on possible enactment of emergency laws in the event the 
UN Security Council decides to impose sanctions against North 
Korea over the issue of nuclear arms development and said: "It 
will depend on contents of sanctions. We have to decide at that 
time whether we need to enact emergency laws." In this way, he 
explained his understanding that emergency laws will be needed 
depending on the contents of the Security Council's sanctions. 
  Regarding a possible case of preventing, as part of the 
sanctions, people from sending money from Japan to North Korea, 
Takatoshi Koto, director of the Ministry of Finance's [MOF] 
International Finance Bureau, said: "We treated cases in the 
past in line with the contents of the [UN] resolutions by 
issuing MOF notifications on the basis of the Foreign Exchange 
Control Order." In this way, he suggested that the MOF will deal 
with the issue of remitting money to North Korea by issuing its 
notifications. They made these remarks in response to questions 
asked by Shozo Kusakawa (of Komeito) and Hidenao Nakagawa (of 
the Liberal Democratic Party). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-28479 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas112__a94014" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-112-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll: Majority Supports SDF's PKO Participation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll: Majority Supports SDF's PKO Participation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1006133694 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 9 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 1 </F>

<F P=103> OW1006133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 21 and 22 May, YOMIURI SHIMBUN conducted a 
nationwide public opinion poll on people's view on the 
Self-Defense Forces [SDF] which will mark the 40th anniversary 
of its establishment in July. Fifty-three percent of the 
respondents have a good impression of the SDF. The rating 
exceeded 50 percent for the first time since the first public 
opinion poll on this issue was conducted in 1984. 
  Asked about whether the SDF is constitutional, 53 percent 
answered it is "constitutional," 22 percent, it is "not," and 25 
percent "refrained from answering." Concerning the necessity 
of the SDF, 84 percent said it is "necessary," representing an 
overwhelming lead over the 10 percent of respondents who said it 
is "not." On the question of in which areas the SDF has been 
"useful," 74 percent answered ensuring national security, 95 
percent, disaster relief; 92 percent, cooperation in people's 
livelihood. Such a high percentage of favorable views 
illustrates the fact that the SDF has taken root among the 
people. Regarding SDF's future participation in UN peacekeeping 
operations (PKO), over 70 percent also said it is "necessary." 
  This is the fourth time the impression of the SDF has been 
surveyed, following polls conducted in 1984, 1988, and 1991. 
The rate of respondents having "favorable impression" or 
"rather" favorable impression reached over 30 percent in 1991, 
and had shown a slightly rising tendency. However, the 
percentage in the most recent poll increased by 13 points, 
compared to the result of the previous poll. It is believed 
that the SDF's activities in Cambodia, where the SDF 
participated in a PKO mission for the first time, improved its 
image. On the other hand, 14 percent, the lowest figure ever, 
said they have a "bad" impression. 
  With regard to the SDF's future participation in PKO, 23 
percent said it is "not necessary" or "not really necessary," 
while 71 percent -- more than three times those respondents 
answering in the negative -- said participation is "necessary" 
or "probably necessary." These results show that most people 
think it is natural for the SDF to participate in UN-led 
international contribution programs. However, regarding the 
question of unfreezing its participation in UN peacekeeping 
forces (PKF) acting as buffer forces and in other missions, 
which is a focal point in revising the PKO Cooperation Law, 
nearly one-half of the respondents answered, "the ban should 
remain as it is for the next several years." Thus, most 
respondents expressed a cautious view. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

