<H3> <TI>   Kumagai on Five-Year Administrative Reform Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kumagai on Five-Year Administrative Reform Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0906023194 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 7 Jun 94 
Evening Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0906023194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At a meeting of the first subcommittee of the House 
of Representatives Budget Committee held on the morning of 7 
June, Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai stated his views 
on how to proceed with future administrative reform, saying: 
"We will draw an outline for the immediate future as early as 
possible by forming an effective deliberation mechanism to work 
closely with the tax reform committee (of the ruling parties)." 
  He added: "In the long-term, a five-year plan will be 
formulated." 
  Kumagai's remarks indicated the government plans to draw up 
a 
five-year administrative reform plan, and deal with it through 
the implementation of a two-tier package consisting of short and 
mid-to-long-term plans. 
  He was replying to a question asked by Noboru Usami from 
Sakigake [Harbinger]. 

</TEXT>

