<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Cooperation Discussed With Brunei </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economic Cooperation Discussed With Brunei </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1106103394 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 11 Jun 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> BK1106103394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Thailand has asked Brunei to step up economic 
cooperation by jointly investing in a fertiliser plant and 
buying more rice, Foreign Minister Prasong Sunsiri said 
yesterday. 
  Brunei's Foreign Minister Prince Mohamed Bolkiah said he 
would consider the proposal to enter a joint venture to produce 
fertiliser from Brunei, Squadron Leader Prasong said. 
  Brunei has limited investments overseas because it is a 
small 
country, Sqn. Ldr. Prasong quoted the prince as saying. 
  But there was no word on Thailand's proposal to buy more 
rice. 
  "We asked Brunei to buy more Thai rice because Thailand 
continues to suffer a deficit in bilateral trade," Sqn. Ldr. 
Prasong said. 
  Prince Bolkiah heads home today at the end of a three-day 
visit. 
  He paid a courtesy call on Prime Minister Chuan Likphai at 
Government House yesterday. 
  Discussions over the past three days also covered 
opportunities for Thai workers in Brunei. 
  According to Sqn Ldr Prasong, Brunei is satisfied with the 
performance of Thai workers and prospects for them may broaden 
as the oil-rich state puts more effort into development. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

