<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Gives War Death Toll Statistics </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Gives War Death Toll Statistics </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1306114094 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network in Vietnamese 
1430 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1306114094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network </F>
<F P=105>  Vietnamese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Ministry of Labor, War Invalids, and Social 
Welfare held a news conference on 10 June on issues related to 
war victims in Vietnam. According to incomplete statistics, 
almost three million people were killed in the war including one 
million soldiers from throughout the country and more than four 
million people were wounded. The war also left 170,000 aged 
homeless persons who now depend on the assistance of their 
countrymen and social welfare centers. More than two million 
people were affected by toxic chemicals and about 500,000 
children were deformed. 
  Implementing and developing the nation's humanitarian 
tradition, our party, state, and people have applied various 
forms of assistance to help these war victims. However, this is 
a wide-scale and very difficult, complicated task that cannot be 
resolved by the Labor, War Invalids and Social Welfare Ministry 
alone. It needs the special attention and assistance from the 
entire society, genial persons, and humanitarian and charitable 
organizations at home and abroad. 
  Assistance programs for these war victims should include 
measures to restore and promote their physical fitness; help 
relieve their difficulties in the daily life; and create 
conditions for them to participate in various social activities, 
especially in productive labor. This will enable them to live 
peacefully with other people in society. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

