<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visitor to DPRK Relays Kim Il-song Remarks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Visitor to DPRK Relays Kim Il-song Remarks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1106235894 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2210 GMT 11 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1106235894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["KYODO and YONHAP report from Tokyo"] </F>
  [Text] Japan's KYODO News Agency reported: North Korean 
President Kim Il-song said that North Korea can abandon its 
nuclear development program if it can receive economic support 
from the United States to convert its graphite-moderated reactor 
to a light-water reactor, along with the normalization of 
diplomatic relations with the United States through dialogue. 
  Selig Harrison, senior associate of the Carnegie Endowment 
for Northeast Asian Security Affairs, said in his news 
conference with KYODO News Agency: President Kim expressed that 
he has the intention to stop the radiochemical laboratory and 
the ongoing construction of a 200,000 kilowatt nuclear reactor 
if the United States and other foreign countries promise to 
provide technology to North Korea for building the light-water 
reactor. Harrison, who paid a week-day visit to Pyongyang at 
the invitation of North Korea, met with President Kim on 9 June 
and held talks with other North Korean high-level leaders, 
including First Vice Foreign Minister Kang Sok-chu. After this, 
he arrived in Beijing on 10 June. 

</TEXT>

