<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Foreign Minister: No Nuclear Inspection </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Foreign Minister: No Nuclear Inspection </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1106005294 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0000 GMT 11 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1106005294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Yi Myong-ku from Berlin] </F>
  [Text] North Korean Foreign Minister Kim Yong-nam said 
that North Korea will not accept nuclear inspection and will 
resolutely deal with outside sanctions including those by the 
United Nations. Kim Yong-nam who arrived in Berlin on 9 June 
without giving any explanation claimed that since North Korea 
withdrew from the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty, it has no 
duty to implement the nuclear inspection. 
  Kim Yong-nam said that North Korea will receive nuclear 
inspection only when a package settlement is reached regarding 
the nuclear issue through DPRK-U.S. talks and when North Korea's 
special status is dissolved. 
  During the news conference held at the second North Korean 
mission in Berlin, Kim Yong-nam emphasized that since the United 
States is the ringleader and offender who introduced the nuclear 
issue to the Korean peninsula and since North Korea is the 
victim, the nuclear issue can be resolved only through talks 
with the United States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

