<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Tok: DPRK Aims To Develop Nuclear Arms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kim Tok: DPRK Aims To Develop Nuclear Arms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1306101894 Seoul YONHAP in English 1009 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1306101894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 13 (YONHAP) -- The recent series of 
behaviors North Korea showed in the course of nuclear talks have 
fed the suspicion that North Korea actually aims to develop 
nuclear arms instead of seeking to obtain diplomatic gains 
through the nuclear issue, Kim Tok, director of the Agency for 
National Security Planning said on Monday. 
  "It now appears their ultimate aim is to develop nuclear 
arms 
and they are employing a delaying tactics to earn a time," Kim 
said. 
  Speaking at a National Defense Committee session, the 
intelligence chief said his agency has been running an early 
warning system against North Korea around the clock in close 
cooperation with the intelligence networks of Korea's allies. 
  He said that thus far there have been no direct signs of 
military provocation on the part of North Korea, though some 
unusual symptoms such as expanded offensive military exercises 
and the tightened grip of people's control were detected. 
  Saying that the coercive control of people seems to have 
reached a point where it no longer works effectively due to 
mounting difficulties like food and energy crises, Kim said 
there is the danger that North Korea may choose to foment an 
external crisis to sidestep their acute internal problems. 
  "Nonetheless, I believe it would be not easy for the North 
to 
unleash a military provocation because they themselves well know 
a war means their suicide," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-28616 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas113_d_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-113 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul, Japan, U.S. Agree on Phased Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seoul, Japan, U.S. Agree on Phased Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1106090494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0855 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1106090494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 11 (YONHAP) -- South Korea, Japan and 
the United States agreed through chain talks Saturday to seek 
phased U.N. sanctions against North Korea. 
  Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu met with U.S. Undersecretary 
of 
State Peter Tarnoff and Japanese Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa 
and concluded that sanctions are inevitable now when the 
opportunity for measurements from North Korea's nuclear reactor 
is damaged, ministry spokesman Chang Ki-ho said. 
  Kakizawa, agreeing with Han that close 
Seoul-Tokyo-Washington 
cooperation is necessary in dealing with the North Korean 
situation, made clear that his country will take responsible 
actions "within limits of the Japanese Constitution" when the 
U.N. Security Council decides to act, Chang said. 
  The two foreign ministers also agreed that China's role is 
critical in solving the North Korean nuclear problem. Kakizawa 
said he plans to seek Beijing's active influence when he meets 
Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen during his China visit. 
  Kakizawa, moreover, pledged his government's efforts to have 
the G-7 summit next month declare its firm will to deter North 
Korea's nuclear development, Chang said. He apologized for 
former Japanese Justice Minister Shigeto Nagano's controversial 
remarks about Tokyo's responsibilities for World War II, saying 
it was "extremely regrettable" to have hurt the feelings of the 
Korean people. 
  Kakizawa and Tarnoff had flown in over the weekend for key 
talks on the North Korean nuclear controversy, on its collision 
course with the U.N. after Pyongyang refused demands by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) to have its nuclear 
reactor fuel rods measured by the agency. 
  Foreign Minister Han met earlier in the day with Tarnoff and 
explained President Kim Yong-sam's trip to Russia this month and 
his talks with U.N. and Chinese officials, the spokesman said. 
  Tarnoff had flown in from Tokyo and briefed Han on what he 
discussed with Japanese officials. 
  Han and Tarnoff exchanged views on upcoming Seoul-Pyongyang 
visits by former U.S. President Jimmy Carter next week and 
agreed that the visit should be used as an opportunity to relay 
firm will of the international community to North Korea. 
  They both evaluated the Friday's IAEA resolution as a 
reflection of the hardline stance of the global community 
regarding the North Korean nuclear situation, Chang said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-28617 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas113_d_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-113 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presidential Secretary on Sanctions on DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Presidential Secretary on Sanctions on DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1306030494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0255 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1306030494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 13 (YONHAP) -- A senior presidential 
secretary said Monday the government favors the imposition of 
step-by-step sanctions on North Korea, responding to reports 
that the United Nations Security Council is considering adopting 
a milder sanctions resolution than originally expected. 
  The secretary said, "South Korea and the United States have 
already agreed on gradual sanctions, and it is wrong to 
interpret these gradual sanctions as appeasement or a retreat." 
  Although the UN resolution would not be strongly worded, he 
added, it would involve practical measures against North Korea 
rather than carrying only symbolic meaning. 
  "The UN Security Council also considered the Chinese 
position, among others, before deciding its course on adopting a 
resolution on gradual sanctions," he said. 
  Reports that China would give military support to North 
Korea 
if war broke out on the Korean peninsula are based merely on 
rumor, he said. 
  Russia has proposed an "eight-way conference" to solve the 
nuclear problem, but it is not a precondition for Moscow's 
participation in sanctions against North Korea, according to the 
official. 
  "I don't think that Russia would oppose the UN Security 
Council resolution on gradual sanctions," he predicted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

