<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japanese Spokesman on `Required Responsibilities' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japanese Spokesman on `Required Responsibilities' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1106120994 Seoul YONHAP in English 1204 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1106120994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 11 (YONHAP) -- Japan will assume all its 
required responsibilities when the U.N. Security Council decides 
on sanctions against North Korea, Seiji Morimoto, Japanese 
Foreign Ministry spokesman, said Saturday. Japan, South Korea 
and the United States did not discuss sanctions outside the 
United Nations at the tripartite talks in Washington, he said. 
  Morimoto gave a press conference at the end of talks between 
Japanese Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa and his South Korean 
counterpart Han Sung-chu. Kakizawa, who flew into Seoul earlier 
Saturday, called on President Kim Yong-sam. 
  "The Japanese Government did not discuss specifics on 
sanctions against North Korea so far," said Morimoto, "but we 
are discussing the purpose of the sanctions and how to go about 
it within a big framework." 
  The spokesman, as did Kakizawa, denied reports that Tokyo 
was 
passive about the sanctions. 
  Asked about possibility of Japan's rearmament caused by 
North 
Korea's nuclear development, Morimoto reminded that Japan is the 
sole victim of a nuclear bomb. He said Japan will strictly 
adhere to its three principles -- not to develop, possess or 
introduce nuclear weapons. 
  On groups of Japanese Socialist Party lawmakers visiting 
North Korea, Morimoto said they are irrelevant to the stance of 
the Japanese Government. "It is a matter entirely up to each, 
individual lawmaker," he said. 

</TEXT>

