BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 11 (YONHAP) -- Japanese Foreign Minister 
Koji Kakizawa denied press reports that Japan is passive about 
sanctions against North Korea in his talks with President Kim 
Yong-sam, presidential spokesman Chu Ton-sik said Saturday. Kim 
met Kakizawa who flew into Seoul earlier and discussed North 
Korea's nuclear situation, Chu said. 
  They agreed that the situation is at a critical point for 
not 
only South Korea and Japan but for the entire Northeast Asia and 
the Pacific region in terms of peace and stability, the 
spokesman said. 
  The Japanese foreign minister promised his country's utmost 
efforts within the boundary of the Constitution to participate 
in U.N. sanctions against North Korea, Chu said after the 
Kim-Kakizawa talks. 
  "The foreign minister said Japan takes the problem as its 
own 
and explained he will deliver such stance when he visits China 
and seek Beijing's cooperation in resolving the problem through 
the United Nations," said Chu. 
  Kakizawa apologized for the controversial remarks by former 
Justice Minister Shigeto Nagano, who said Japan was not an 
aggressor in World War II but just trying to free Asian colonies 
from European grip. "It was wrong for former Minister Nagano to 
say such nonsense and discomfort South Korea," he was quoted as 
saying. 

</TEXT>

