<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-113 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seeks `Gradual' Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seeks `Gradual' Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1106120694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1144 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1106120694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 11 KYODO -- Japanese and South Korean 
foreign ministers agreed Saturday [11 June] that sanctions 
against North Korea for its failure to guarantee nuclear 
transparency should be gradual, Japanese officials said. 
  Japanese Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa and his South Korean 
counterpart Han Sung-chu met for one and a half hours in Seoul 
and confirmed that planned U.N. Security Council sanctions 
against North Korea are aimed at encouraging Pyongyang to hold 
dialogue for a negotiated solution, the officials said. 
  Kakizawa and Han pledged close bilateral cooperation in 
dealing with North Korea's suspected nuclear arms development 
program, they said. 
  The Japanese foreign minister made clear that Japan will 
"make utmost efforts within the Constitution" if the Security 
Council decides to adopt sanctions. 
  Kakizawa dismissed reports that Japan is intransigent on 
taking punitive steps against North Korea, in an apparent denial 
of an article published in THE NEW YORK TIMES on Thursday 
claiming Japan is reluctant to levy sanctions. 
  They also verified a trilateral agreement between Japan, 
South Korea and the U.S. on June 4 that the three countries 
would hold close contact while the U.N. discusses measures. 
  The ministers reiterated that China's role in defusing the 
nuclear crisis is important, saying they must urge China not to 
use its veto when the Security Council votes on sanctions. 
  Kakizawa told Han he will urge China to play an active role 
in settling the nuclear dispute when he visits China on Sunday. 
  In Beijing, Kakizawa is expected to ask Chinese Foreign 
Minister Qian Qichen for China's support for a resolution by 
the Security Council against Pyongyang. 
  China has repeatedly expressed hope that the North Korean 
nuclear crisis could be resolved through negotiations. 
  Kakizawa also held a meeting the same day with South Korean 
President Kim Yong-sam, in which Kim said relatively lengthy 
U.N. Security Council discussions on sanctions against North 
Korea may help Pyongyang return to the negotiating table, the 
officials said. 
  Kim called such discussions a meaningful process for urging 
North Korea to make its nuclear program more transparent, they 
said. 

</TEXT>

