<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Undersecretary Tarnoff Continues Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Undersecretary Tarnoff Continues Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets With President Kim </H4>

<F P=102> SK1106062994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0612 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1106062994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 11 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam 
met with visiting U.S. Undersecretary of State Peter Tarnoff 
Friday morning to discuss joint Korea-U.S. action on the North 
Korean nuclear row. 
  During the hour-plus meeting at Chongwadae, they shared the 
view that a resolution on sanctions against North Korea will 
inevitably be adopted by the United Nations Security Council 
  Senior Presidential Press Secretary Chu Ton-sik told 
reporters that President Kim and Tarnoff agreed the firm 
relations between Korea and the United States were easing 
Koreans' anxiety over the nuclear wrangling. 
  Tarnoff said that "despite the escalating tension on the 
Korean peninsula, Koreans are wisely coping with it and this is 
impressive." 
  President Kim offered an explanation: "Korean people are now 
mature enough to trust the government's security policies as the 
government does not exploit security issues for political power 
any more." 
  "Some Americans worry about the security of Korea, but they 
will be relieved to see Koreans' firm security posture and 
maturity," the undersecretary noted. 
  As to former U.S. President Jimmy Carter's planned visit to 
Pyongyang, President Kim expressed some concern. "Kim Il-song is 
likely to utilize Carter's visit as a tactic of dialogue and 
smile toward the Western community," he said. 
  Tarnoff explained President Bill Clinton believes that 
Carter's trip should not be an obstacle to UN Security Council 
sanctions against North Korea. 
  Touching on North Korea's repeated call for direct talks 
with 
the United States, Kim and Tarnoff agreed it was a tactic 
designed to secure the withdrawal of American troops from South 
Korea. 
  Earlier in the day, Tarnoff held talks with Deputy Prime 
Minister Yi Hong-ku on similar issues. 

</TEXT>

