<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Undersecretary Tarnoff Continues Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Undersecretary Tarnoff Continues Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Remarks on DPRK, Carter Cited </H4>

<F P=102> SK1106095994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0952 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1106095994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 11 (YONHAP) -- U.S. Undersecretary of 
State Peter Tarnoff on Saturday denied former President Jimmy 
Carter will carry any message from Washington to North Korea. He 
also denied speculations that the United States shifted from its 
earlier position and is now willing to engage in Moscow-proposed 
multilateral conference to defuse the North Korean nuclear 
crisis. 
  Tarnoff, heading home after his two-day visit to Seoul, said 
at an airport news conference that the priority focus is to push 
a sanction resolution at the United Nations. 
  U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher, emerging from 
talks with Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev, was quoted 
as saying that Washington is willing to positively consider the 
eight-way conference Russia suggested to discuss the North 
Korean nuclear issue. For now, adopting a Security Council 
resolution has to come foremost than any multilateral 
conference, Tarnoff said, adding that the resolution will be 
ready within days. 
  Tarnoff was optimistic about China's cooperation on U.N. 
resolution, saying that Beijing fully understands the 
seriousness of the current situation. Knowing that, China will 
act in harmony as a member of the international community, he 
said. 
  Asked whether Carter will carry any message from President 
Bill Clinton when he visits North Korea next week, the 
undersecretary emphasized that the ex-President goes to North 
Korea as a private citizen. Washington, therefore, has no 
intention to deliver a message through him, he said. 

</TEXT>

