<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former U.S President Carter Arrives 13 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Former U.S President Carter Arrives 13 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1306073594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0727 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1306073594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 13 (YONHAP) -- Former U.S. President 
Jimmy Carter flew into Seoul Monday in a prelude to his visit to 
North Korea, with the possibility of his mediation in the 
nuclear crisis gaining widespread attention. 
  Carter is visiting the two Koreas as head of his private 
peace center. He meets with South Korean Foreign Minister Han 
Sung-chu and President Kim Yong-sam before passing through the 
heavily fortified truce village of Panmunjom into the North 
Wednesday [15 June]. 
  He is expected to meet North Korean leader Kim Il-song, who 
is reportedly waiting for Carter to deliver a message to U.S. 
President Bill Clinton on his proposal for defusing the current 
nuclear tensions. 
  The former president will return to Seoul June 18 via 
Panmunjom and hold a press conference before heading back to the 
United States the same day. 
  Carter goes to Pyongyang as the U.N. Security Council 
prepares to circulate a U.S.-drafted resolution seeking punitive 
sanctions against the communist state for reneging on nuclear 
inspections by the International Atomic Energy Agency. 

</TEXT>

