<DOCNO> FBIS4-28643 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas113_d_94037" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-113 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Decides To Strengthen Civil Defense </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Decides To Strengthen Civil Defense </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1306070694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0656 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1306070694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 13 (YONHAP) -- As tension mounts over 
the nuclear dispute with North Korea, the government has decided 
to strengthen the civil defense structure by checking and 
revamping civil defense organizations and facilities. 
  Under the decision made at a Central Civil Defense Council 
Meeting presided over by Prime Minister Yi Yong-tok Monday, the 
government will also increase civil defense-related educational 
and public relations programs to focus public attention on 
national security. 
  An emergency call-up exercise will be conducted Wednesday 
and 
Thursday to check the mobilization status of 6.6 million 
reservists for civil defense. 
  Air-raid shelters, emergency water supply systems and 
warning 
systems will be tested and renovated, if need be, by the end of 
the month in full preparation for any emergencies. 
  The air-raid drill on Wednesday will focus on evacuation to 
shelters, vehicular traffic control, first aid for the injured 
and emergency reconstruction of destroyed facilities. 
  The Ulchi defense exercise slated for late August will serve 
as an overall test of the government's ability to manage a 
crisis -- not only an emergency in the run-up to war but also a 
flood, fire or other disaster. 
  The government should keep the public informed of every 
security development to ensure that they do not fear for their 
safety and willingly participate in civil defense drills, Prime 
Minister Yi told the meeting. 
  Emergency preparations should be carried out in such a 
manner 
that neither will they cause the people excessive uneasiness nor 
will they provide any reason for North Korea to make military 
provocations, he stressed. 
  Attending the meeting were Economic Planning Minister Chong 
Chae-sok, National Unification Minister Yi Hong-ku, Home 
Minister Choe Hyong-u, Defense Minister Yi Pyong-tae and 
Emergency Planning Committee Chairman Chon Yong-taek, among 
others. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

