<H3> <TI>   Reports on Issues Related to DPRK Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports on Issues Related to DPRK Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kakizawa on Talks Prerequisite </H4>

<F P=102> OW1106020394 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 1000 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1106020394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report; from "NHK News 7" program] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa has said that as a 
prerequisite to North Korea resuming negotiations with the 
United States, North Korea should first guarantee it will accept 
international nuclear inspections. Kakizawa spoke at the upper 
house Budget Committee session on 10 June in reference to North 
Korea's position that, if U.S.-North Korea talks on the issue of 
suspected nuclear development programs are resumed, it is 
willing to accept inspections by the International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA). 
  Questioning Kakizawa during the session, Keiji Kajiwara of 
the Social Democratic Party of Japan noted North Korean Foreign 
Minister Kim Yong-nam has said his country is willing to accept 
nuclear inspections if U.S-North Korean negotiations resume. 
And, Kajiwara asked how the Japanese Government views this. 
  Kakizawa said there exist differences of view between the 
United States and North Korea over the questions of resuming 
U.S.-DRPK talks and the timing of IAEA inspections. He said the 
matter should be settled in a way to guarantee nuclear 
inspections by the IAEA. 
  Kakizawa thus said that as far as Japan is concerned, 
nuclear 
inspections must come first before North Korea and the United 
States resume their talks. 

</TEXT>

