<H3> <TI>   Reports on Issues Related to DPRK Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports on Issues Related to DPRK Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Tokyo To Bank on PRC's Persuasion </H4>

<F P=102> OW1106095494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0946 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1106095494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hamamatsu, June 11 KYODO -- Japan will continue 
efforts via China to persuade North Korea to change its stance 
on the suspected nuclear weapons development program, the chief 
government spokesman said Saturday [11 June]. 
  Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai, in a lecture in 
this 
central Japanese city, said there is "a strong possibility" that 
the United Nations Security Council will adopt a resolution 
against North Korea in a week or 10 days unless Pyongyang 
reconsiders its stance on the issue. 
  Kumagai said Japan's basic policy will remain unchanged over 
the issue, as the government of Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata has 
resolved. 
  He noted the absence of China's objection to a sanctions 
resolution adopted Friday by the International Atomic Energy 
Agency against North Korea. China abstained instead of voting 
against it. 
  Kumagai also said the nuclear issue poses to Japan a policy 
choice of whether to continue or abandon 50 years of alliance 
with the United States since the end of World War II. 

</TEXT>

