<H3> <TI>   Reports on Issues Related to DPRK Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports on Issues Related to DPRK Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hata Cautious About Sanctions </H4>

<F P=102> OW1306055894 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 0300 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1306055894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video; from the "NHK News" </F>
program] 
  [Text] Commenting on possible sanctions against the DPRK 
(North Korea) because of its suspected development of nuclear 
arms, Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata said at a meeting of the House 
of Councillors' Budget Committee this morning that it would be 
difficult under the constitution for Japan to take part even in 
nonmilitary measures, if they formed an integral part of 
military action. 
  [Begin Hata recording] In terms of rear support, we will be 
able to offer medical services or other forms of assistance 
after hostilities have ended -- such as, for instance, the 
minesweeping operations we did after the Gulf War. However, 
operations which are an integral part of military action or the 
use of force will be very difficult. [end recording] 
  Prime Minister Hata's remarks indicated that under the 
constitution, it would be difficult for Japan to participate 
even in nonmilitary operations which are an integral part of 
military action. 
  Commenting further on intragovernmental deliberations on 
responding to a United Nations decision to impose sanctions, 
Hata said that while Japan was still persuading DPRK to seek a 
solution through dialogue, it might give the wrong message to 
North Korea to make public the detailed substance of such 
deliberations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

