<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reports on Issues Related to DPRK Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports on Issues Related to DPRK Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    IAEA Action `Unlikely' To Affect DPRK </H4>

<F P=102> OW1106004694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0023 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1106004694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 11 KYODO -- North Korea is unlikely to 
change its hard-line stance with the resolution adopted by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) to suspend technical 
aid for its refusal to accept full nuclear inspections, Ministry 
of Foreign Affairs [MOFA] sources said Saturday. 
  The IAEA action could affect the UN Security Council, 
however, on its deliberations on possible economic sanctions on 
North Korea, the sources said. 
  In an overwhelming vote of 28-1, the Vienna-based IAEA 
adopted the resolution, setting in motion the first punitive 
step by the UN nuclear watchdog agency against North Korea. 
  The Japanese Government welcomed the IAEA action as the 
international community's expression of concern against the 
North. 
  But Pyongyang could "not care less" about the suspension of 
the IAEA's technical aid, which amounted to 270,000 dollars in 
1993, the Foreign Ministry source said. 
  The government expects the action will have some influence 
on 
potential UN sanctions against North Korea, and Japan is 
determined to persuade China not to exercise a veto if the 
measure is put to a vote at the Security Council, the sources 
said. 
  China, a key ally of North Korea, has a veto power on a 
resolution as one of the five permanent security council members. 
  Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata said Friday night he thinks the 
row over North Korea's suspected nuclear development program has 
become increasingly tense, saying, "we cannot put off (taking 
actions) forever." 
  Hata told reporters, however, that the IAEA measures are not 
"a punishment" and that Japan still hopes the issues will be 
resolved through dialogue among concerned nations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

