<H4>    Kakizawa Leaves for ROK, PRC </H4>

<F P=102> OW1106013394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0101 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1106013394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 11 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Koji 
Kakizawa left Saturday for South Korea and China to hold talks 
with his counterparts on ways to deal with a deepening crisis 
over North Korea's alleged nuclear weapons program. 
  Kakizawa is expected to use his talks Saturday with South 
Korean Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu and South Korean President 
Kim Yong- sam to reconfirm a determination among Japan, South 
Korea and the United States to get tough on Pyongyang and 
prepare punitive action against its secretive nuclear program. 
  South Korea may brief Kakizawa on Kim's visit to Russia and 
Uzbekistan and Han's visit to New York and Beijing, Japanese 
Foreign Ministry officials predicted. 
  In Beijing on Sunday, Kakizawa will ask Chinese Foreign 
Minister Qian Qichen for China's support for a resolution by the 
UN Security Council against Pyongyang, Foreign Ministry 
officials said. 
  China has repeatedly expressed hope that the North Korean 
nuclear crisis could be resolved through negotiations. 
  Japanese, South Korean and U.S. officials are counting on 
the 
powerful UN panel to move on the resolution as early as next 
week. 
  Kakizawa and his South Korean and Chinese counterparts will 
also take up other issues, including the summit of the Group of 
Seven (G- 7) economic powers in Naples, Italy in July. 

</TEXT>

