<H4>    Kakizawa, Han Reaffirm Close Contact </H4>

<F P=102> OW1306073094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0700 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1306073094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 13 KYODO -- Japan's and South Korea's 
foreign ministers reconfirmed Monday that they will maintain 
close contact in dealing with the North Korean nuclear crisis, 
Japanese Foreign Ministry officials said. 
  Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa and his South Korean 
counterpart Han Sung-chu, who met Saturday in Seoul, had a 
10-minute telephone conversation Monday, the officials said. 
  Kakizawa called Han to brief the South Korean minister on 
Kakizawa's visit to China on Sunday, they said. 
  He told Han that he was able to share concern and 
acknowledgement with Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen that 
the situation concerning North Korea's alleged attempts to 
develop nuclear weapons is very grave and difficult, the 
officials said. 
  Kakizawa and Qian also agreed on the importance of 
cooperation among South Korea, Japan and China, and permanent 
and nonpermanent members of the U.N. Security Council, the 
officials quoted Kakizawa as saying. 
  Han told Kakizawa he hopes Kakizawa's visit to China would 
help China play a constructive role in solving the problem, they 
said. 

</TEXT>

