<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reports on Issues Related to DPRK Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports on Issues Related to DPRK Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hata on Nonmilitary Support </H4>

<F P=102> OW1306072794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0711 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1306072794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 13 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
said Monday that Japan can engage only in nonmilitary support in 
UN or other multinational forces operations in the event of an 
international crisis. 
  Hata made the remark at a meeting of the House of 
Councillors 
Budget Committee in reply to Makoto Taneda, legislator from the 
Social Democratic Party, the No. 2 opposition party. 
  "Medical services or minesweeping following the end of 
fighting, such as those Japan carried out in the Persian Gulf, 
could be possible," Hata said when asked what kind of support 
Japan can provide. "But it would be extremely difficult to 
engage in those united with military actions." 
  As for the right of collective security in the UN Charter, 
Takao Ode, director general of the cabinet legislation bureau, 
said Japan owns the right as a sovereign state, but cannot 
execute it because of the constitution that renounces war. 
  "The pacifism and the spirit of international cooperation in 
the preamble of the constitution agree with the ideas in the UN 
Charter," Ode said. "Japan will do its duty within the 
Constitution, and cannot use, or threaten to use, forces banned 
in Article 9 of the Constitution." 
  Regarding possible UN sanctions against North Korea over its 
suspected nuclear development program, Hata declined to say what 
steps Japan can take in the sanctions because of an anxiety "of 
sending the wrong message" to North Korea. 
  Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa told the same session Japan 
and South Korea have agreed that the sanctions should not be 
punitive, but should be those urging North Korea to return to a 
safeguard system of the International Atomic Energy Agency. 
  Hata told reporters earlier in the day that Japan supports 
the resolution of the North Korean nuclear issue through 
dialogue. 
  Meanwhile, a government source said Japan cannot take the 
initiative and needs to "give priority to the intentions of 
South Korea." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

