<H3> <TI>   Reports on Issues Related to DPRK Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports on Issues Related to DPRK Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Iran's Testing of DPRK Missile Denied </H4>

<F P=102> OW1306115094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1130 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1306115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 13 KYODO -- The Iranian Embassy in 
Tokyo on Monday [13 June] denied as "absurd" an allegation that 
Iran has test-fired Nodong missiles supplied by North Korea and 
insisted that Tehran's nuclear program is "peaceful." 
  Iranian Ambassador to Japan Hoseyn Kazempur-Ardabili, in a 
letter dated Monday and received the same day, took issue with a 
KYODO NEWS SERVICE story Sunday that had said Japan is 
reportedly pressuring Iran to stop test-firing the North 
Korean-made missiles. 
  The story quoted the latest edition of the U.S. NEWS AND 
WORLD REPORT as saying the Japanese Government is threatening to 
suspend financial assistance to a 1.2 billion dollar dam project 
in Iran unless Tehran stops the missile testing. 
  The envoy said the missile allegation "has been denied time 
and again at the highest level of my government and Japanese and 
South Korean officials have been amply and convincingly assured 
of (its) absurdity." 
  He said that raising it at the time, with the growing 
tension 
on the Korean peninsula and concern about it in Japan, "is 
another attempt to undermine the friendly relations between Iran 
and Japan." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

