<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `No Decision' on Suspending Aid to PRC </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `No Decision' on Suspending Aid to PRC </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1306111994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1026 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1306111994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 13 KYODO -- Japan has made no decision 
on whether or not it will suspend economic assistance to China 
after it conducted an underground nuclear test last Friday [10 
June], Vice Foreign Minister Kunihiko Saito said Monday. 
  Saito told a press conference the government has not yet 
made 
a decision on whether it should immediately change its Official 
Development Assistance (ODA) policy toward China. 
  He said Japan has conveyed its concern about the test and 
explained again the contents of its ODA guidelines hammered out 
in 1992, which state that recipient countries should promote 
disarmament. 
  Japan will continue to urge China to stop conducting nuclear 
tests, he said. 
  Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa suggested in Beijing on 
Sunday 
that China's nuclear test could influence Tokyo's future loans 
to China. 

</TEXT>

