<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   LDP Official Comments on Need To Form Coalition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    LDP Official Comments on Need To Form Coalition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1306090494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0831 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1306090494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 13 KYODO -- Liberal Democratic Party 
(LDP) President Yohei Kono may not be the logical choice for the 
next prime minister to lead a new coalition government joined by 
the LDP, a senior LDP member said Monday [13 June]. 
  "President Kono is the LDP's best candidate," said Koichi 
Kato, an ex-chief cabinet secretary of a now-deposed LDP 
government, at a news conference. 
  "But it is impossible for the LDP to form a government by 
itself and we need to put together a coalition," he said. "We 
should therefore seriously weigh the possibility of installing 
someone from non-LDP forces (as the next premier)." 
  Kato, who heads a policy study group within the LDP dubbed, 
"Group New Century," is a known archrival of Kono and has been a 
staunch critic of the current LDP leadership. 
  Describing the current administration of Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata as a weak regime that cannot win trust domestically 
or internationally, the vocal lawmaker said the LDP should map 
out a clear-cut strategy for creating a new, stable government 
and demand Hata's resignation. 
  To fashion a fresh government with the participation of 
broader political forces, the LDP, ousted from power last summer 
for the first time in 38 years, needs to discuss with other 
major political parties whether they can govern together, Kato 
said. 
  But he took a dim view of the LDP's tie-up with Shinseito 
unless Ichiro Ozawa, the ruling coalition's back room deal 
maker, gives up the idea of running politics from behind the 
scenes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-28665 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas113_a_94022" </HT>


