<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Urges JNP To Lead Political Realignment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hosokawa Urges JNP To Lead Political Realignment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1106044994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0417 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1106044994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 11 KYODO -- Former Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa urged members of the Japan New Party (JNP) on 
Saturday to take the lead in an expected further realignment of 
political forces under the new electoral system. 
  Hosokawa told a party convention of its representatives 
nationwide that "the JNP should play a pioneering role in the 
second stage of political realignment even with a resolution to 
dissolve the party for the sake of reform." 
  Hosokawa also demanded that the opposition Social Democratic 
Party (SDP) [SDPJ -- Social Democratic Party of Japan] return to 
the ruling coalition, saying, "if the SDP decides to join hands 
with us, we will not spare any effort (to bring that about)." 
  The national convention is the first since the JNP was 
established in May 1992. 
  More than 70 members of both Diet chambers and 
representatives from local chapters attended the meeting, at 
which they will set the party's key policies and reappoint 
Hosokawa as party leader. 
  Hosokawa told reporters Friday [10 June] night that the 
parliamentary group "Kaishin," of which the JNP is a member, is 
likely to evolve into a new party within a few months. 
  He said Kaishin, whose members include the JNP, Shinseito 
(Japan Renewal Party) and Democratic Socialist Party (DSP), will 
seek broad participation, including the SDP, the largest 
opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and the new party 
Sakigake. 
  He said before Kaishin becomes a political party, it needs a 
few months until a new electoral map is drawn for 300 
single-seat districts under the new electoral system. 
  A new political reform law for the lower house enacted in 
January calls for electing 300 legislators from single-seat 
districts and 200 via proportional representation. 
  On allegations that he received 100 million yen as illegal 
donations from the Sagawa Kyubin trucking business group, 
Hosokawa told the JNP convention that Diet testimony by his 
former aide Masatoshi Miyama will show his innocence. 
  Upon demand by opposition parties, Miyama is to testify 
under 
oath Wednesday at the House of Representatives budget committee 
on the money scandal. 
  Hosokawa's questionable personal finances led his 
resignation 
as premier in April in part to take responsibility for a delay 
in Diet deliberations on the fiscal 1994 state budget. 
  "Through the testimony by my former secretary Miyama, I 
think 
(the opposition) can understand what I have said," Hosokawa said. 
  Hosokawa has repeatedly denied charges that the money was an 
illicit donation, saying he took the 100 million yen from Sagawa 
as a loan in 1982 and had repaid it with interest by 1991. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-28666 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas113_a_94023" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-113 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   JNP To Seek Dissolution of Kaishin Group </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    JNP To Seek Dissolution of Kaishin Group </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1106112494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0957 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1106112494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 11 KYODO -- Former Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa was reelected as chief of the Japan New Party 
(JNP) on Saturday [11 June] and urged the party to be ready to 
dissolve itself for the sake of political reconfiguration and 
reform. 
  Addressing the JNP's national convention, Hosokawa said the 
party should "play a pioneering role in the second stage of 
political realignment even with a resolution to dissolve the 
party for the sake of reform." 
  Hosokawa also vowed the party's utmost efforts to bring the 
Social Democratic Party (SDP) back to the ruling coalition as 
part of efforts to jointly tackle a number of issues of 
immediate concern. 
  "If the SDP decides to join hands with us, we will not spare 
any effort to lay the groundwork for its return to the 
coalition," said Hosokawa, who resigned the premiership in April 
to take the blame for his alleged financial improprieties. 
  The national gathering, the first since the JNP set up shop 
in May 1992, brought together over 70 members of both houses of 
the Diet and representatives from local chapters of the party. 
  At the convention, the JNP approved its action plan for 1994 
in which the party promised to seek the dissolution of the 
parliamentary group Kaishin, of which the JNP is a member, while 
groping for a strong political power base with other parties. 
  The SDP, now the second-largest opposition force, walked out 
of the coalition in April in protest against the formation of 
Kaishin by other coalition partners without the SDP. The SDP's 
departure forced Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata to form the first 
minority government since 1955. 
  The JNP also approved the new leadership under Hosokawa. 
Satsuki Eda, former leader of the United Social Democratic 
Party, a minor political force that disbanded in May, and Yuriko 
Koike were elected the party's deputies, while Masuo Matsuoka 
was retained as representative secretary general. 
  At a news conference held after the party meeting, Hosokawa 
spoke of the need for coalition parties to take a united front 
in achieving administrative and economic reforms by setting 
aside key policy differences. 
  "We are now in a state of emergency," he said. "We must ride 
out the stormy weather at sea." 
  Hosokawa expressed hope the Diet testimony by his former 
aide 
Masatoshi Miyama will help dispel allegations that he received 
100 million yen in illegal donations from a scandal-tainted 
trucking firm. Hosokawa says the money was a loan he repaid 
later. 
  He also said he will testify before the Diet himself if the 
legislature decides to summon him as a sworn witness. 
  Miyama is to testify under oath on the money scandal at the 
House of Representatives budget committee on Wednesday. 
  Hosokawa has repeatedly denied charges that the money was an 
illicit political contribution, saying he accepted the 100 
million yen from the Sagawa Kyubin group in 1982 and had repaid 
it with interest by 1991. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

