<DATE1>  13 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Comments Concerning Economic Recovery </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Comments Concerning Economic Recovery </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Mieno: `One Step' Toward Recovery </H4>

<F P=102> OW1306075694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0632 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1306075694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 13 KYODO -- Japan's economy has moved 
"one step" toward recovery, but some concern still remains, such 
as the yen's rise, Bank of Japan Governor Yasushi Mieno said 
Monday [13 June]. 
  "Assessing the recent economic indicators, there seems to be 
high chances that the economy has moved one step toward a 
recovery," Mieno told the Budget Committee of the House of 
Councillors. 
  The governor said the "one step" was from his latest 
assessment that the economy is "showing signs of bottoming out." 
  Mieno cited brighter signs in personal consumption, 
inventory 
adjustments and exports, particularly to Southeast Asian 
nations, and noted that corporate concern about having a surplus 
of facilities and equipment has "hit a ceiling." 
  His comments came after the central bank released Friday its 
quarterly "Tankan" report on business sentiment that showed 
improvement in confidence by both major manufacturers and 
nonmanufacturers for the first time in five years. 
  Asked about the effects of the 5.5 trillion yen income tax 
cuts, Mieno said he expects the cuts to "support the economy 
that is showing slight brightness." 
  But Mieno said he remains uncertern if the economy has moved 
"two or three steps forward," noting such prevailing concerns as 
the yen's rise, sluggish corporate capital investment and 
competition from other Asian nations. 
  As for capital investment, however, he said the environment 
for a recovery is improving, and stressed that declines in 
interest rates since the central bank cut its official discount 
rate to an all-time low of 1.75 percent last year are still 
supporting corporate restructuring efforts. 
  The central bank intends to continue carefully watching to 
see whether the recent bright spots spread to the economy as a 
whole, Mieno said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

