<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Comments Concerning Economic Recovery </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Comments Concerning Economic Recovery </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Saito Sees `Signs' of Recovery </H4>

<F P=102> OW1306092494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0906 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1306092494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 13 KYODO -- Recent economic indicators 
have presented "signs for the economy to recover," Vice Finance 
Minister Jiro Saito said Monday [13 June]. 
  "Our assessment is not much different from the Bank of 
Japan," Saito told reporters, agreeing to earlier comments by 
central bank governor Yasushi Mieno that the economy is poised 
to take the recovery path. 
  However, Saito, like Mieno, remained cautious, saying, "We 
still can't declare with confidence that the economy will head 
toward a recovery." 
  Mieno told the Budget Committee of the House of Councillors, 
"assessing the recent economic indicators, there seems to be a 
high possibility that the economy has moved one step toward a 
recovery." 
  His comments were a step forward from his latest assessment 
that the economy is "showing signs of bottoming out," after the 
central bank released its quarterly "Tankan" business sentiment 
survey for may on Friday showing broad-based improvement for the 
month for the first time in five years. 
  Asked about the effects from continuing 5.5 trillion yen 
worth of income tax cuts, Mieno said he expects to "support the 
economy that is showing brightness." 
  But Mieno said he does not know if the economy has moved 
"two 
or three steps" forward, noting such prevailing concerns as the 
yen's rise, corporate capital investment and competition with 
other Asian nations. 

</TEXT>

