<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Comments on Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Comments on Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1206084394 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0818 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1206084394 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Foreign Minister Kim Yong-nam on Nuclear Issue of Korean </F>
Peninsula" -- KCNA headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, June 12 (KCNA) -- Vice-premier and 
Foreign Minister Kim Yong-nam called a press conference in 
Berlin on June 10 and clarified the principled position of the 
Democratic People's Republic of Korea concerning the nuclear 
issue including its essence, core reactor refueling and a 
solution to the issue. 
  Answering questions put by reporters, he said: 
  "The great leader President Kim Il-song made it clear more 
than once long ago that our country has neither intention nor 
capacity to manufacture nuclear weapons. 
  "What do we need such weapons for? The 'nuclear issue' of 
our country was raised because the United States has been 
suspicious of our peaceful nuclear activities from the beginning. 
  "As our country has foundations of the independent national 
economy and a powerful defence capacity, any 'sanctions' can 
never frighten us," he declared, and said: 
  "We demand that the United States respond to talks for a 
peaceful solution to the issue with due attention. It would be 
well advised to be clearly mindful that if it failed to respond 
to the talks, trying to resolve the issue with pressure and 
'sanctions', it will result only in causing tension on the 
Korean peninsula." 
  Kim Yong-nam declared that the Korean people will achieve 
national reunification independently in accordance with the 
three principles of independence, peaceful reunification and 
great national unity." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

