<H3> <TI>   `No Sanction Steps Can Frighten Us' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `No Sanction Steps Can Frighten Us' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1106232194 Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 2212 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1106232194 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 2212 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Kim Yong-nam held 
a news conference in Berlin, Germany, on 10 June. Reporters of 
foreign newspapers, news agencies, and radio in Germany attended 
the news conference. The foreign minister, who spoke at the 
news conference, talked about our principled position on the 
nuclear issue -- including the essence of the nuclear issue on 
the Korean peninsula, the replacement of fuel rods, and the 
method of resolving the nuclear issue -- and answered reporters' 
questions by saying: Over the past few years, the great leader 
Comarde Kim Il-song has already declared on many occasions that 
our country has no intention nor capacity to produce nuclear 
weapons. If we have them, where can we use them! The nuclear 
issue of our country has been raised because the United States 
has dealt with us from the beginning with its doubts on our 
peaceful nuclear activity. 
  He stressed that because our country has a foundation of 
self- reliant national economy and a powerful defensive 
capability, no sanction steps can frighten us, and he continued: 
We demand that the United States respond to talks with its 
interest to peacefully resolve the issue. The United States 
should clearly know that if it does not come to the talks, but 
rather tries to resolve the issue with its pressure or 
sanctions, it will only aggravate tensions on the Korean 
peninsula. 

</TEXT>

