<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Differences' Remain in Auto Trade Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Differences' Remain in Auto Trade Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1106091494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0902 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1106091494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 11 KYODO -- The United States has 
demanded in the resumed "framework" trade talks that Japanese 
automakers adopt specific purchase plans for U.S.-made parts, 
government sources said Saturday. 
  The demand for the purchase plans as part of "objective 
criteria" for improving foreign access to the Japanese market 
was made in subcabinet-level framework talks on auto trade held 
Friday and Saturday in Tokyo, the sources said. 
  U.S. officials also demanded as part of the criteria that 
Japanese-owned auto assembly plants in the U.S. increase the 
local content ratio in their production, the sources said. 
  The Japanese side did not directly respond to the U.S. 
demands and asked that further discussions be held at the 
working-level talks starting Monday, they said. 
  Japan told the U.S. at the beginning of the resumed talks 
that it would not accept any numerical targets as objective 
criteria for improving market access in Japan. 
  At the talks, both Japan and the U.S. presented their own 
versions of a draft agreement on auto trade, the sources said. 
  U.S. officials also asked that a bilateral agreement 
incorporate plans for purchases of U.S.-made auto parts that 
five Japanese automakers recently announced, the sources said. 
  An official of Japan's Ministry of International Trade and 
Industry told reporters that serious differences remain on key 
issues of auto trade in the talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

