<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meeting With U.S. Semiconductor Firms Deadlocked </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meeting With U.S. Semiconductor Firms Deadlocked </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1006145394 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 10 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 11 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1006145394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Senior officials from major Japanese and U.S. firms 
in the semiconductor industry held a meeting on 9 June, followed 
by a joint news conference later on. The Japanese and U.S. 
Governments are to hold discussions to make a decision by July 
on whether to terminate the bilateral semiconductor agreement 
ahead of its scheduled expiration in July 1996. However, 
differences in opinion between the two nations have come into 
the picture, for Japan is calling for an early termination of 
the agreement while the United States insists that it remain in 
effect. 
  At the news conference, Hidehiko Yoshida (vice president of 
the Toshiba Corporation), chairman of the Users Committee of 
Foreign Semiconductors, who represented the Japanese side, 
emphasized that "the situation between the Japanese and U.S. 
industries is satisfactory in terms of cooperative ties." Gil 
Amelio (president of the National Semiconductor Corporation), 
chairman of the U.S. Semiconductor Industry Association (SIA), 
also pointed out that the "U.S. and Japanese semiconductor 
industries have become more and more mutually dependent." 
  As for the bilateral semiconductor agreement, however, 
Yoshida said: "The foundation has been laid for the industries 
of both nations to continue cooperating. The private sector 
should be left alone to look after its own affairs." He thus 
indicated that the private sector wants the Japanese and U.S. 
Governments to promptly terminate the semiconductor arrangement. 
  However, Amelio clearly indicated opposition to terminating 
the arrangement, saying: "The semiconductor agreement has 
brought progress in establishing cooperative ties between the 
U.S. and Japanese industries. Therefore, the arrangement should 
be continued." 
  A "20-percent" share of Japan's market for foreign 
semiconductors has been designated as a target goal in the 
semiconductor agreement. Regarding this point, Yoshida said: "In 
the past, this figure has tended to take on a life beyond the 
purpose for which it was originally intended. I feel it is no 
longer necessary to set figures." In contrast, Wilf Corrigan 
(chairman of LSI Logic), a member of the SIA Board of Directors, 
stressed, "Figures are needed to measure progress." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

