<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Issues Related to DPRK Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Issues Related to DPRK Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Former Prime Minister's Widow Invited by DPRK </H4>

<F P=102> OW1306012394 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 12 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1306012394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mrs. Mutsuko Miki, widow of the late former Prime 
Minister Takeo Miki, will visit the DPRK (North Korea) on a 
week-long stay. She is one of the women who have called for the 
establishment of a Japan-ROK-DPRK women's organization called 
"Peace in Asia and the Role of Women" which holds seminars to 
discuss such issues as the resolution of the conflict between 
the ROK and the DPRK and Japan's postwar settlements. When she 
attended a seminar held in Pyongyang in 1992, she received a 
direct invitation from DPRK President Kim Il-song to visit North 
Korea together with her family. She said she accepted the 
invitation, in the hope that it might "help contribute to the 
promotion of Japan-DPRK exchanges." 
  In connection with the DPRK nuclear issue, there is a rush 
of 
visits to the DPRK by Japanese politicians. For example, the 
Social Democratic Party of Japan has already sent a delegation, 
and House of Representatives members Taku Yamazaki and Yoichi 
Tani of the Liberal Democratic Party are scheduled to visit on 
14 June. Amid the flurry of political visits, Mrs. Miki said: 
"I have been making preparations since late last year. There 
are no plans for me to meet government officials (in connection 
with the nuclear issue). It is purely a family trip." 

</TEXT>

